    "content": "U.S. Representative Ilhan Omar of Minnesota introduced a resolution in the House of Representatives on Wednesday urging the United States to become a member of the International Criminal Court (ICC). The resolution, if adopted, would call on the U.S. government to sign and ratify the Rome Statute, the treaty establishing the ICC.\n\nThe ICC, based in The Hague, Netherlands, prosecutes individuals for genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes, and the crime of aggression. The United States has not joined the court, citing concerns about potential prosecutions of American citizens. Previous administrations have taken varying positions, with the Bush administration withdrawing President Clinton's signature in 2002 and later passing laws opposed to the court.\n\nOmar, a Somali-American lawmaker, has a background in human rights advocacy and previously called for accountability for atrocities in Somalia. For the Somali diaspora, this resolution resonates as many fled conflict and human rights abuses in Somalia. The ICC has investigated crimes in neighboring countries, and some Somalis hope for justice for past abuses. However, the resolution faces long odds in the current political climate, as many U.S. lawmakers remain skeptical of the court.\n\nThe resolution is co-sponsored by a small group of progressive lawmakers. It would require a two-thirds majority in the Senate to ratify the Rome Statute, making adoption unlikely in the near term. Nonetheless, the introduction highlights ongoing debates about U.S. engagement with international institutions and accountability for mass atrocities.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/warbixin-ilhaan-cumar-oo-ku-baaqday-in-mareykanku-ku-biiro-maxkamadda-dambiyada-caalamiga-ah/423793/",
